article.headline: Kings close it out with 10-2 run
article.linkText: Visiting Kings manage to outlast Bucks
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings left Milwaukee flattered and victorious. The Bucks did their best imitation of the Kings' precision passing and sharp shooting, but they came up just short at the Bradley Center on Tuesday night, falling to the Kings 124-117. "Amazing offensive game," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. Peja Stojakovic had 31 points and sank all four of his free throws in the final 20 seconds to secure the win for Sacramento. The teams combined to make 55 of 85 first-half shots and shoot a collective 55 percent overall in a thriller that featured more assists (72) that rebounds (70). "I looked up in the second quarter and I was like, 'Man, those are end-of-the-game numbers right there," Bucks forward Joe Smith said. "In order for us to get back into that game, we had to do the same things they were doing, move the ball, be unselfish and get everybody involved." The Bucks took a 115-114 lead on Michael Redd's layup with a 1:02 left, but Vlade Divac's wide-open 15-foot jumper gave the Kings the lead for good 20 seconds later and sparked a game-ending 10-2 run. "Both teams shot it well," Adelman said. "We finally got some stops at the end." The Bucks had a chance to send the game into overtime after Stojakovic's two free throws made it 120-117 with 17 seconds left. But Desmond Mason fired a hurried-up, off-balance 3-pointer that missed badly with 8 seconds left. "We wanted to make him take a tough shot," Adelman said. "We really wanted to keep it out of Redd's hands." Brad Miller, who scored 21 points, then sank four free throws in the final seven seconds. Mike Bibby scored 24 points for the Kings. Mason and Toni Kukoc each scored 21 off the bench for Milwaukee. Bucks first-year coach Terry Porter played for Adelman for nine seasons in Portland, then coached with him in Sacramento last year. It sure showed. "These two teams are very similar," Kings center Vlade Divac said. "It was hard. They were running our plays and we were running their plays. Terry ran most of the same plays, you think you would be able to stop. But people made a lot of shots. It was a shootout." The Kings shot a sizzling 69 percent in the first half -- and only led 65-62 because the Bucks shot 61 percent. Milwaukee took its first lead at 72-71 on Redd's 3-pointer, and the Bucks, who trailed by 15 early on, took an 88-83 lead before Bibby's five points helped Sacramento close the third quarter on an 8-0 run. Before tip-off, Porter spoke about how the Kings, the NBA's highest scoring team, have perfected the backdoor cuts popularized by assistant coach Pete Carril, whose methodical Princeton teams always struggled to score. "If you can get better talent to run your system, you can get better results," Porter said with a chuckle. He wasn't laughing an hour later, however, when the Kings schooled his Bucks in the finer points of backdoor baskets. Stojakovic burned Tim Thomas for an easy one on the game's first possession, and by the second half, Thomas was on the bench and the Bucks were throwing anybody they could at the 6-foot-10 Stojakovic, including Redd, who is 6-6, and Damon Jones (6-3). "It's a tough cover. It's no different than Tracy McGrady," Porter said. "Timmy just lost him a couple times. In the second half we just tried to put quicker guys on him and it worked a little." The Bucks fell behind 37-22 in the first quarter but got right back in it by mimicking the Kings' patient and potent offensive scheme. "They shoot the ball so well," Kings guard Doug Christie said. "Especially when they get in a transition game a little bit, get a little energy and before you know it, everything is falling." Until the final minute, when the Bucks couldn't match Sacramento's suddenly stifling defense. "I don't feel bad," Porter said. "I'm disappointed at the start, obviously, but they're the best team in the league. They came in here and we gave them a good run."

Game notes
Sacramento had 25 assists in the first half. ... With everybody shooting so well, both teams had just three offensive rebounds by halftime. ... The Kings have won five straight over Milwaukee, which lost for just the second time in its last 17 home games. ... Christie was raked across his right eye by Thomas on a 3-pointer in the opening minutes. After a timeout, Christie stayed in the game.
